<subSubSection id="334973947A838B2E4047F39BCD46E796" pageId="0" pageNumber="185" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="58FF287892708095DDF7A83ACB206894" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E002D29EFDE002833AAF1C27F35D14A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis id="65CA43AF25099CB6EE89268A94165CE3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">Female</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F548EC06CB84D7687AA38324A3794EE3" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">29</figureCitation>
). Body length 6.4 mm, forewing length 5.5 mm; black, with the following parts yellow: the base of mandible, lateral longitudinal band along clypeus, elliptic interantennal spot, scape ventrally, ocular sinus, a line behind eyes at gena, two anterior interrupted spots of pronotum dorsally, tegula (except brownish red at middle), parategula, two anterior interrupted spots on metanotum, mid coxa ventrally, apices of fore and mid femora, fore and mid tibiae (slightly dark ventrally), hind tibia dorsally, tarsi, apical bands of T1-T2 and S2, and mandible mostly; fore wing with an apical dark spot. Clypeus flat in the middle part, without lateral longitudinal raised carina, with extremely fine sparse punctures, and smooth, apical margin a bit emarginated and almost truncated (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CA5D0BC3C506B5DD042692AF5DD764D8" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">30</figureCitation>
); frons with sparse punctures in the middle part, interspaces with extremely fine punctures (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FE464CFE41F12D3B64A536925FDF7DDD" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">30</figureCitation>
); posterior area of hind ocelli with a row of slightly long longitudinal carina (longer than other species) along occipital carina in the middle area, occipital carina dorsally developed and complete, with thick hair (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="ABD1103EC8EDECDBDBE65788245C8F30" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">31</figureCitation>
), not sinuate as in 
<taxonomicName id="5539DADE5E97D4FCFC413767412189B1" class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. darugiriensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="185" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="darugiriensis">
<emphasis id="46B00B6E991C1A565F6A322497283C65" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">P. darugiriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2489A21D933707DED5CD786EA85AFB42" captionStart="Figures 1–10" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 10. Paraleptomenes setaceus sp. nov. Holotype (♀): 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 10 paratype (♂): 2, 4, 6, 8. 1, 2 habitus (dorsal view) 3, 4 head (frontal view) 5 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 6 A 6 - A 13 7 mesosoma (dorsal view) 8 metasoma (ventral view) 9 tegula (dorsal view) 10 mesosoma (lateral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures1-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677827" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">5</figureCitation>
); anterior face of pronotum with a large deep fovea in the middle (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1F96EB2424C55546194D345546BFE691" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">31</figureCitation>
); mesoscutum with sparse punctures in the posterior half, interspaces with extremely fine punctures (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="21471143EA0587DB4F1EA3C78AD94D71" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">33</figureCitation>
); scutellum and metanotum with sparse punctures, interspaces with extremely fine punctures, scutellum nearly flat in lateral view, scutellum at the same level as the mesoscutum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A1FBE820F2C44FCCC8675BF6127BE29F" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 29 - 33. Paraleptomenes nurseanus montanus Giordani Soika, 1994. ♀ 29 - 33 29 habitus (dorsal view) 30 head (frontal view) 31 vertex and part of pronotum (dorsal view) 32 mesosoma (lateral view) 33 mesosoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185">32</figureCitation>
); posterior surface of propodeum with irregular striae and few punctures; T1 elongated, almost hemispheric, T1 slightly concave near the end, both T2 and S2 with apical lamellae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="BFC90AB96C578262501F20B672FD3599" doi="10.3897/jhr.90.82546.figures29-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677830" pageId="0" pageNumber="185" start="Figures 29–33" startId="F4">
